Tutorial 3 - Soar Your Backend Development with Deno

Tutorial 3 - Soar Your Backend Development with Deno

8 steps

Now that you are familiar with how to use the Deno CLI and the JSR, let's use Deno on a simple backend project.

Learn how to use Oak, a middleware framework that works well with Deno, in building your backend from handling HTTP requests and responses to managing authentication routes.

You will learn how to perform CRUD operations with a sqlite package for Deno, and how to use the WebCrypto API for a JWT package with djwt. You will also learn to hash passwords with argontwo.

With these things combined, you will gain a base knowledge for developing backend servers with Deno.

Let's Soar with Deno in this tutorial!

For technical help on the StackUp platform & quest-related questions, join our Discord, head to the | quest-help-forum channel and look for the correct thread to ask your question.

This campaign will only cover Linux or MacOS platforms. If you are a Windows user, please use GitHub Codespaces for a uniform and streamlined developer experience.

Prerequisites

  • Familiarity with Javascript or Typescript
  • Required to have finished Tutorial 1 and Tutorial 2
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Familiarity with Javascript or Typescript
  • Required to have finished Tutorial 1 and Tutorial 2. You will be using the same project throughout all the module.

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Use Deno for backend development
  • Use @oak/oak middleware framework
  • Perform CRUD operations with SQLite databases using @db/sqlite
  • Sign and verify using WebCrypto API for JWT with @zaubrik/djwt
  • Hash passwords with @denosaurs/argontwo

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 8

  • Step 1: Creating A Simple Route with oak

    Before you try to do anything, let's clean up our development environment.

    Delete any files you have and directories within the root directory of the project EXCEPT the .git directory if you have one. Your explorer should look empty.

    Now create a new file called deno.json. Once created, run the following command.

    deno add jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3

    This command should update your deno.json and generate a new lock file deno.lock.

    Next, create a file called main.ts. Write the following code.

    import { Application, Router } from "@oak/oak"

const router = new Router();
const app = new Application();
const controller = new AbortController();

router.get("/hello", (ctx) => {
    ctx.response.body = "Hello, World!";
})

app.use(router.allowedMethods());
app.use(router.routes());

if (import.meta.main) {
    app.listen(
        {
            port: 5555,
	     signal: controller.signal
        }
    )
}
    TypeScript

    If you are receiving linting errors like "ImportMeta main not found", try pressing the following keys in succession and combination: hold Ctrl+Shift then press P. Then type "Deno Enable". It should select the first found VSCode command. Press Enter. This should create a .vscode folder with a settings.json containing the following contents.

    {
    "deno.enable": true
}
    TypeScript

    It should fix most of the linting issues you get. The previous lint errors are not from Deno but from the built-in Typescript support in VSCode.

    Now run the following command.

    deno run -A main.ts

    The flag used here is -A, which is a shorter flag for --allow-all, which means allow all access. This also means you don't get the prompts you usually get since we have explicitly told the runtime to allow all access.

    This should start an HTTP server at port 5555. In the case you accidentally closed the terminal or closed the process itself, you can always run the same command on another terminal. Ensure only one is running.

    Run the following curl command to check that it works.

    curl http://127.0.0.1:5555/hello

    This should output "Hello, World!".

    Next, let's create another route that only accepts GET methods. Just append this code below just below line 9.

    router.get("/close", (ctx) => {
    ctx.response.body = "Bye!";
    controller.abort("User has invoked to close the connection");
})
    TypeScript

    Restart the server. Then run the following command.

    curl http://127.0.0.1:5555/close

    This should close your HTTP server because of the AbortController() which sends a signal to our process to terminate itself once an abort operation is called.

    Well done! You have learned how to create a simple route with just GET methods. One route is at the path /hello which returns a response body "Hello, World!". The second route is at the path /close which aborts the running server, killing it entirely.

    Receiving POST Request Data

    Your next goal would be to perform requests using the POST method. To allow the backend server to receive such requests, let's declare a POST route at the path. But you still have to create a type to easily handle the requested data.

    At the root directory of the project, create a directory called types. Then head over to the types directory and create a file called user.ts. Write the following code into user.ts.

    export default interface User {
        id: number;
        username: string;
        password: string;
        salt: string;
}
    TypeScript

    Next, create a file called request.ts in the same directory. Write the following code into request.ts.

    export interface RegisterData {
    username?: string,
    password?: string
}

export interface LoginData extends RegisterData {};
    TypeScript

    Save both files. Next, head back to the root directory of the project and open main.ts. Add this line of code on line 2.

    import { LoginData, RegisterData } from "./types/request.ts";
    TypeScript

    Then at the line just below where we declare the /close path, add the following code snippet.

    router.post("/register", async (ctx) => {
  const registerData: RegisterData | undefined = await ctx.request.body.json();
  if (registerData) {
    console.log(
      `Username is "${registerData.username}" and password is "${registerData.password}"`,
    );
  }
});

router.post("/login", async (ctx) => {
  const loginData: LoginData | undefined = await ctx.request.body.json();
  if (loginData) {
    console.log(
      `Username is "${loginData.username}" and password is "${loginData.password}"`,
    );
  }
});
    TypeScript

    Run the following command on a new terminal.

    deno run -A main.ts

    Run the following command on another terminal.

    curl http://127.0.0.1:5555/register -XPOST -d '{"username":"stacker", "password":"stackersecure"}'

    Your terminal that runs the deno command should have the following output.

    Username is "stacker" and password is "stackersecure"
  • Step 2: Adding The Database

    You have prepared some routes that do not require authentication and authorisation. Two of those routes are necessary so that a user can register and log in to get authenticated and gain authorisation. These are /register and /login.

    You already wrote the necessary types to receive register and login data which are RegisterData and LoginData.

    The next thing you should do is extend the functionality of those two routes rather than just outputting the Username is "stacker" and password is "stackersecure". But first, you have yet to scaffold the following components of your backend.

    • The database
    • The cryptographic logic

    Let's first add the database. At the root directory of your project, run the following command.

    deno add "jsr:@db/sqlite@^0.12.0"

    Create a new directory called database. Then inside the database directory, create a file called mod.ts. Write the following code to mod.ts.

    import { Database } from "@db/sqlite";
const db = new Database("./database/users.db");

const create_table_command = `
        CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS users(
                id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
                username TEXT NOT NULL,
                password TEXT NOT NULL,
                salt TEXT NOT NULL
        )
`;

if (db.open) {
        db.exec(create_table_command);
} else {
        console.error("DB is not connected");
        Deno.exit(1);
}

export default db;
    TypeScript

    Head back to the root directory of your project. Open deno.json. Let's add an import map to our database code. Edit deno.json so it will look like the following code.

    {
  "imports": {
    "@db/sqlite": "jsr:@db/sqlite@^0.12.0",
    "@oak/oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3",
    "~database": "./database/mod.ts"
  }
}
    JSON

    The name ~database is purely preference, specifically the addition of the tilde character (~). This is intentional as it helps us differentiate between an import map of a file import and an import map of JSR and npm packages.

  • Step 3: Cryptographic Logic

    The next part is adding our cryptographic logic for authentication using argontwo and authorisation using djwt.

    argontwo is a package that contains crypto logic based on the battle-tested argon2 password hashing algorithm. It also has a feature to include a salt which is a randomised set of characters grouped in varied lengths. A salt is needed to decrease the chances of hash collisions.

    A hash collision is when two or more sets of data return the same hash. But no two people should have the same hash even if they have the same password through this method called salting.

    djwt is a package that allows us to generate JSON Web Tokens (JWT). You will be using a web standard called SubtleCrypto to perform signing and verifying JWT.

    Let's first install the dependencies argontwo and djwt. Run the following command at the root directory of your project.

    deno add "jsr:@denosaurs/argontwo@^0.2.0" "jsr:@std/crypto@^1.0.3" "jsr:@std/encoding@^1.0.5" "jsr:@zaubrik/djwt@^3.0.2"

    Let's start implementing the JWT logic as it's pretty straightforward. Head to the root directory of your project. Create a directory called crypto. Create a file in the crypto directory called jwt.ts. Write the following code to jwt.ts.

    import { create, getNumericDate, verify } from "@zaubrik/djwt";
import type User from "~types/user";

/**
 * Our JWT key to be used to generate the signature.
 */
const key = await crypto.subtle.generateKey(
  { name: "HMAC", hash: "SHA-512" },
  false,
  ["sign", "verify"],
);

/**
 * Generates a Json Web Token (JWT) for user login authentication.
 * This JWT is used throughout a user's session until it expires.
 * @param payload User data such as username and id
 * @param origin domain name of source origin
 * @returns `Promise<{string|undefined, number} | undefined>`
 */
const generateJwt = async (payload: User | undefined, origin: string) => {
  if (!payload) return payload;

  /**
   * **N**ot **B**e**F**ore
   */
  const nbf = new Date();
  nbf.setDate(nbf.getDate() + 365);

  const jwt = await create({
    alg: "HS512",
    type: "JWT",
  }, {
    exp: getNumericDate(nbf),
    aud: origin,
    user: payload.username,
  }, key);

  return { jwt, nbf };
};

/**
 * Verifies the signature of the JWT
 * @param jwt The JWT signature
 * @returns `string` value as the username.
 */
const verifyJwt = async (jwt: string) => {
  const payload: { user: string } = await verify(
    jwt,
    key,
  );

  return payload;
};

export { generateJwt, verifyJwt };
    TypeScript

    You will notice that the type User is erroring. To fix that, open and edit deno.json from the root directory of your project. You will add an import map to both crypto/jwt.ts, types/request.ts and types/user.ts. It should look like the code snippet below.

    {
  "imports": {
    "@db/sqlite": "jsr:@db/sqlite@^0.12.0",
    "@denosaurs/argontwo": "jsr:@denosaurs/argontwo@^0.2.0",
    "@oak/oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3",
    "@std/crypto": "jsr:@std/crypto@^1.0.3",
    "@std/encoding": "jsr:@std/encoding@^1.0.5",
    "@zaubrik/djwt": "jsr:@zaubrik/djwt@^3.0.2",
    "~database": "./database/mod.ts",
    "~types/user": "./types/user.ts",
    "~types/request": "./types/request.ts",
    "~crypto/jwt": "./crypto/jwt.ts"
  }
}
    JSON

    Next, create a file in the crypto directory called auth.ts. Write the following code to auth.ts.

    import { verifyJwt } from "~crypto/jwt";
import type { Context, Next } from "@oak/oak";

/**
Checks if user is authenticated by checking the request cookie
and the Authorization header. Then the JWT tokens are pulled
from both cookie and header and then compared if it matches.

If they don't match, then function just early returns with
null/undefined.

Otherwise, `next` function will be called.
 */
const checkAuth = async (
  ctx: Context,
  next: Next,
) => {
  const pathname = decodeURIComponent(ctx.request.url.pathname);
  if (!pathname.startsWith("/auth")) {
    ctx.response.status = 404;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: "Bad Request",
      status: 404,
    };
    return;
  }

  const jwtFromCookie = await ctx.cookies.get("user");
  const authHeader = ctx.request.headers.get("Authorization");
  console.info(
    `Has Cookie: ${jwtFromCookie !== undefined}\nHas Auth Header: ${
      authHeader !== null
    }`,
  );
  console.info("Cookie", jwtFromCookie);
  const [, jwt] = authHeader ? authHeader.split(" ") : [null, null];

  if (!jwt || !jwtFromCookie) {
    ctx.response.status = 403;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: "Missing credentials. Not authenticated.",
      status: 403,
    };
    return;
  }

  if (jwt === jwtFromCookie) {
    const payload1 = await verifyJwt(
      jwtFromCookie,
    );

    const payload2 = await verifyJwt(
      jwt,
    );

    if (payload1.user === payload2.user) {
      ctx.response.status = 200;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: "Authenticated",
        status: 200,
      };
    }
  } else {
    ctx.response.status = 403;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: "Not authenticated",
      status: 403,
    };
    return;
  }

  return await next();
};

export default checkAuth;
    TypeScript

    The checkAuth function is used to check the user's session cookie and the authorization header if both signatures can be verified and their payload matches. The reason for this duality is important because in some scenarios, logged-in users might want to use the JWT signature string for performing API calls without the need for a session cookie.

    But this session cookie is needed for a prolonged session for the user while also ensuring that the cookie's JWT signature matches the one received from the authorization header.

    This function is used in your case for simulating a logged-in user performing API calls that require authentication.

    Create the file pwd.tsin the crypto directory. Write the following code to the file pwd.ts.

    import { decodeBase64, encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";
import { type Argon2Params, hash } from "@denosaurs/argontwo";
import "@std/dotenv/load";

const TOKEN = decodeBase64(Deno.env.get("API_KEY") ?? "");
const encoder = new TextEncoder();

export const argon2Verify = (
  password: string,
  salt: string,
  originalHash: string,
): boolean => {
  const encodedPassword = encoder.encode(password);
  const encodedSalt = encoder.encode(salt);
  const params: Argon2Params = {
    algorithm: "Argon2id",
    secret: TOKEN,
    version: 0x13,
  };
  const ret =
    encodeBase64(hash(encodedPassword, encodedSalt, params)) === originalHash;
  return ret;
};

export const argon2Hasher = (password: string, salt: string): ArrayBuffer => {
  const encodedPassword = encoder.encode(password);
  const encodedSalt = encoder.encode(salt);
  const params: Argon2Params = {
    algorithm: "Argon2id",
    secret: TOKEN,
    version: 0x13,
  };
  return hash(encodedPassword, encodedSalt, params);
};
    TypeScript

    You have written two important functions here. Most argon2 interfacing libraries have their own verify function built-in. But it's just a wrapper of the hash function of argon2.

    With this implementation, you learn that to verify a password is to compare hashes between the original hash and the regenerated hash using the password and original salt value.

    The functions argon2Verify and argon2Hasher use a variant of argon2 called argon2id. It is a hybrid combination of the two other variants, argon2i and argon2d. This campaign won't go too deep about the intricacies of argon2 but it's the recommended password hashing algorithm according to OWASP recommendations.

    Edit deno.json again at the root directory of the project. Add import maps for crypto/auth.ts and crypto/pwd.ts. It should look like the code snippet below.

    {
  "imports": {
    "@db/sqlite": "jsr:@db/sqlite@^0.12.0",
    "@denosaurs/argontwo": "jsr:@denosaurs/argontwo@^0.2.0",
    "@oak/oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3",
    "@std/crypto": "jsr:@std/crypto@^1.0.3",
    "@std/encoding": "jsr:@std/encoding@^1.0.5",
    "@zaubrik/djwt": "jsr:@zaubrik/djwt@^3.0.2",
    "~database": "./database/mod.ts",
    "~types/user": "./types/user.ts",
    "~types/request": "./types/request.ts",
    "~crypto/jwt": "./crypto/jwt.ts",
    "~crypto/auth": "./crypto/auth.ts",
    "~crypto/pwd": "./crypto/pwd.ts"
  }
}
    JSON

    The last file you will create is to generate an API Key or TOKEN. Head to the root directory of the project, and create two files, .env and generateToken.ts. Write the following code to generateToken.ts.

    import { crypto } from "@std/crypto";
import { encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";

const apiKey = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(16));
console.log(`GENERATED API_KEY:\`${encodeBase64(apiKey)}\``);
    TypeScript

    The code uses the SubtleCrypto's getRandomValues function which is a pseudo-random number generator. It's cryptographically strong enough to generate random values for our secret API KEY.

    Run the following commands at the root directory of your project.

    deno add jsr:@std/dotenv/load
deno run generateToken.ts

    This will install https://jsr.io/@std/dotenv and also generate your API key. See the screenshot below for what the output can look like.

    Copy the generated API Key between the backticks (`). See the screenshot above as a reference. Then write the following code snippet to your .env file.

    API_KEY="YOUR_API_KEY"
    Plain text

    Replace the value of YOUR_API_KEY with yours.

    Save every file you have not saved yet. Ensure you have followed every step. Yours should look similar to the screenshot below by now.

    The core part of your backend has now been implemented.

    Disclaimer: For now, you are just applying some concepts on hashing, signing and verification. However, in real-world production code, implementing your cryptographic logic using battle-tested cryptographic functions and algorithms still requires you to include heavily testing your backend. It's hard and it's messy and requires more practice. You are still learning the basics. If you want to learn more about securing systems and platforms, you should take a visit to the Open Worldwide Application Security Project (OWASP).

    In the next step, you will write the middleware for registering users and logging in users.

  • Step 4: Register Middleware

    Head to the root directory of your project. Then create a new directory middleware. Then create a file in the middleware directory called register.ts.

    Since you now have the following import maps

    • ~database
    • ~crypto/pwd
    • ~types/user
    • ~types/request

    You can now begin writing the logic for registering and logging in as a user. Open register.ts located in the middleware directory. Then write the following code into register.ts.

    import { crypto } from "@std/crypto";
import { encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";
import type { RouterContext } from "@oak/oak";
import { argon2Hasher } from "~crypto/pwd";
import db from "~database";
import type User from "~types/user";
import { RegisterData } from "~types/request";

const register = async (
  ctx: RouterContext<
    "/register",
    Record<string | number, string | undefined>,
    // deno-lint-ignore no-explicit-any
    Record<string, any>
  >,
) => {
  const registerData: RegisterData | undefined = await ctx.request.body
    .json();

  if (
    !registerData || !registerData.username?.trim() ||
    !registerData.password?.trim()
  ) {
    ctx.response.status = 422;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: "Username or password field cannot be empty.",
      status: 422,
    };
    return;
  }

  const { username, password } = registerData;

  const stmt = db.prepare(
    `
		SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '${username}';
		`,
  );

  const row = stmt.get<User>();
  if (!row) {
    const randSalt = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(32));
    const salt = encodeBase64(randSalt);
    const hashedPassword = encodeBase64(argon2Hasher(password, salt));
    const changes = db.exec(
      `
			INSERT INTO users(username, password, salt) VALUES ('${username}', '${hashedPassword}', '${salt}');
			`,
    );
    if (changes > 0) {
      ctx.response.status = 200;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: `User \`${username}\` is now registered.`,
        status: 200,
      };
      return;
    } else {
      ctx.response.status = 503;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: `Server Error.`,
        status: 503,
      };
    }
  }
  ctx.response.status = 409;
  ctx.response.body = {
    message: `User \`${username}\` already exists.`,
    status: 409,
  };
  return;
};

export default register;
    TypeScript

    Much of the logic here is important for the user to register.

    For example, if one of the user's inputs is empty, this block of code will check that.

    	if (
		!registerData || !registerData.username?.trim() ||
		!registerData.password?.trim()
	) {
		ctx.response.status = 422;
		ctx.response.body = {
			message: "Username or password field cannot be empty.",
			status: 422,
		};
		return;
	}
    TypeScript

    If the user does have valid inputs, then your code will proceed to check if a username already exists in this block of code.

    	const { username, password } = registerData;

	const stmt = db.prepare(
		`
		SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '${username}';
		`,
	);

	const row = stmt.get<User>();
    TypeScript

    The row variable is used to assign the value if there exists a row in the database with the username. If there is no user, then the code will proceed within the following if-block statement.

    if (!row) {
		const randSalt = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(14));
		const salt = encodeBase64(randSalt);
		const hashedPassword = encodeBase64(argon2Hasher(password, salt));
		const changes = db.exec(
			`
			INSERT INTO users(username, password, salt) VALUES ('${username}', '${hashedPassword}', '${salt}');
			`,
		);
		if (changes > 0) {
			ctx.response.status = 200;
			ctx.response.body = {
				message: `User \`${username}\` is now registered.`,
				status: 200,
			};
			return;
		} else {
			ctx.response.status = 503;
			ctx.response.body = {
				message: `Server Error.`,
				status: 503,
			};
		}
	}
	ctx.response.status = 409;
	ctx.response.body = {
		message: `User \`${username}\` already exists.`,
		status: 409,
	};
    TypeScript

    The code within the if-clause will perform operations to register the user's username, the generated hash for the password, and the password salt. This data is then written into the database.

    Then another if-block will check if the operation was a success by checking if there were more than zero changes. Otherwise, this means there is something wrong with the database so it creates a response with status 503 and the message "Server Error.".

    If everything else is covered, that means the user exists already so the code will return a response with status 409 and a message that the user already exists.

  • Step 5: Login Middleware

    Head to the root directory of your project. Head to the middleware directory. Then create a file in the middleware directory called login.ts. Write the following code to login.ts.

    import type { RouterContext } from "@oak/oak";
import { argon2Verify } from "~crypto/pwd";
import { generateJwt } from "~crypto/jwt";
import db from "~database";
import type User from "~types/user";
import { LoginData } from "~types/request";

const login = async (
  ctx: RouterContext<
    "/login",
    Record<string | number, string | undefined>,
    // deno-lint-ignore no-explicit-any
    Record<string, any>
  >,
) => {
  const loginData: LoginData | undefined = await ctx.request.body
    .json();

  if (
    !loginData || !loginData.username?.trim() ||
    !loginData.password?.trim()
  ) {
    ctx.response.status = 422;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: "Username or password field cannot be empty.",
      status: 422,
    };
    return;
  }

  const { username, password } = loginData;

  const stmt = db.prepare(
    `
		SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '${username}';
		`,
  );

  const row = stmt.get<User>();

  if (!row) {
    ctx.response.status = 404;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `User with \`${username}\` does not exist.`,
      status: 404,
    };
    return;
  }

  const { salt: originalSalt, password: originalHash } = row;
  const verified = argon2Verify(password, originalSalt, originalHash);

  if (verified) {
    const jwToken = await generateJwt(row, ctx.request.url.origin);
    if (!jwToken) {
      ctx.response.status = 503;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: "Server Error. Unable to generate JWT.",
        status: 503,
      };
      return;
    }

    await ctx.cookies.set("user", jwToken.jwt, {
      httpOnly: true,
      secure: false,
      signed: false,
      sameSite: "lax",
      expires: new Date(jwToken.nbf),
      path: "/",
    });

    ctx.response.status = 200;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Correct credentials for \`${username}\``,
      status: 200,
    };
    return;
  }

  ctx.response.status = 403;
  ctx.response.body = {
    message: "Unauthorised",
    status: 403,
  };
  return;
};

export default login;
    TypeScript

    Much of the logic here is important for the user to log in. Handling user input is the same as register.ts. The only difference between the two is when a user registers, you need to check if a row does not exist. In contrast, when a user logs in, you need to check that the user exists in the database.

    If a user exists, the code checks if a user's inputted username matches with the username fetched from the database. It also checks the user's inputted password using the argon2Verify function by regenerating the hashed password using the salt fetched from the database.

    If both username and password are not verified, the process skips over the JWT generation and cookie logic and then proceeds to create a response with status 403 and the message "Unauthorised"

    Otherwise, the code generates a JWT and a response cookie holding the value of the generated JWT signature. All the logic can be seen in these lines of code here.

    const { salt: originalSalt, password: originalHash } = row;

  if (argon2Verify(password, originalSalt, originalHash)) {
    const jwToken = await generateJwt(row, ctx.request.url.origin);
    if (!jwToken) {
      ctx.response.status = 503;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: "Server Error. Unable to generate JWT.",
        status: 503,
      };
      return;
    }

   await ctx.cookies.set("user", jwToken.jwt, {
      httpOnly: true,
      secure: false,
      signed: false,
      sameSite: "lax",
      expires: new Date(jwToken.nbf),
      path: "/"
    });

    ctx.response.status = 200;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Correct credentials for \`${username}\``,
      status: 200,
    };
    return;
  }
    TypeScript

    Now that this login logic is done, let's create two more routes in the next step. The first route will be using a PUT method. The second route will be using the DELETE method.

  • Step 6: Examples of Auth Required Routes

    The first route will be using a PUT method. The second route will be using the DELETE method. These two routes will be declared in our code as only accessible for those who are authenticated.

    Update Account

    It would make sense that our first route is related to updating accounts so the PUT method makes sense for this.

    Updating user details is just a modified version of registering a user. So it won't be a surprise if the code used is too similar to register.ts.

    Head to the root directory of your project. Create a new directory in the middleware directory called auth. Create a new file within the auth directory called updateAccount.ts. Write the following code to updateAccount.ts.

    import { crypto } from "@std/crypto";
import { encodeBase64 } from "@std/encoding";
import type { RouterContext } from "@oak/oak/router";
import { argon2Hasher, argon2Verify } from "~crypto/pwd";
import { verifyJwt } from "~crypto/jwt";
import db from "~database";
import type User from "~types/user";
import { RegisterData } from "~types/request";

const updateAccount = async (
  ctx: RouterContext<
    "/auth/update",
    Record<string | number, string | undefined>,
    // deno-lint-ignore no-explicit-any
    Record<string, any>
  >,
) => {
  const registerData: RegisterData | undefined = await ctx.request.body
    .json();

  if (
    !registerData || !registerData.username?.trim() ||
    !registerData.password?.trim()
  ) {
    ctx.response.status = 422;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: "Username or password field cannot be empty.",
      status: 422,
    };
    return;
  }

  const { username: newUsername, password } = registerData;

  const jwtFromCookie = await ctx.cookies.get("user");

  if (!jwtFromCookie) {
    ctx.response.status = 503;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Server Error.`,
      status: 503,
    };
    return;
  }

  const { user: oldUsername } = await verifyJwt(jwtFromCookie);

  const oldStmt = db.prepare(
    `
		SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '${oldUsername}';
		`,
  );

  const newStmt = db.prepare(
    `
		SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '${newUsername}';
		`,
  );

  const oldRow = oldStmt.get<User>();

  if (!oldRow) {
    ctx.response.status = 503;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Server Error.`,
      status: 503,
    };
    return;
  }

  const newRow = newStmt.get<User>();

  if (newRow && oldRow && (newUsername === oldUsername)) {
    if (argon2Verify(password, oldRow.salt, oldRow.password)) {
      ctx.response.status = 304;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: `No changes.`,
        status: 304,
      };
      return;
    }
    const randSalt = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(14));
    const salt = encodeBase64(randSalt);
    const hashedPassword = encodeBase64(argon2Hasher(password, salt));
    const changes = db.exec(
      `
			UPDATE users 
			SET 
				password = '${hashedPassword}',
				salt = '${salt}'
			WHERE
				username = '${oldUsername}'
					`,
    );
    if (changes > 0) {
      ctx.response.status = 200;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: `User \`${oldUsername}\` has changed password.`,
        status: 200,
      };
      return;
    } else {
      ctx.response.status = 503;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: `Server Error.`,
        status: 503,
      };
      return;
    }
  } else if (!newRow) {
    let passwordMessage = "";
    if (argon2Verify(password, oldRow.salt, oldRow.password)) {
      passwordMessage = passwordMessage.concat("Password unchanged.");
    } else {
      passwordMessage = passwordMessage.concat("Password has changed.");
    }

    // We still update the salt at least.
    const randSalt = crypto.getRandomValues(new Uint8Array(14));
    const salt = encodeBase64(randSalt);
    const hashedPassword = encodeBase64(argon2Hasher(password, salt));
    const changes = db.exec(
      `
			UPDATE users 
			SET username = '${newUsername}',
				password = '${hashedPassword}',
				salt = '${salt}'
			WHERE
				username = '${oldUsername}'
					`,
    );

    if (changes > 0) {
      // clears up cookies
      await ctx.cookies.clear({
        httpOnly: true,
        secure: false,
        signed: false,
        sameSite: "lax",
      });
      ctx.response.status = 200;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message:
          `User has changed username. ${passwordMessage} Relogin required.`,
        status: 200,
      };

      return;
    } else {
      ctx.response.status = 503;
      ctx.response.body = {
        message: `Server Bolshit Error.`,
        status: 503,
      };

      return;
    }
  }

  ctx.response.status = 409;
  ctx.response.body = {
    message: `User \`${newUsername}\` already exists.`,
    status: 409,
  };
  return;
};

export default updateAccount;
    TypeScript

    Delete Account

    This logic is short as it only needs a cookie to get the username from the JWT signature. Starting at the root directory of the project, head to the middleware/auth directory. Create a new file called deleteAccount.ts. Write the following code to deleteAccount.ts.

    import type { RouterContext } from "@oak/oak";
import { verifyJwt } from "~crypto/jwt";
import db from "~database";
import type User from "~types/user";

const deleteAccount = async (
  ctx: RouterContext<
    "/auth/delete",
    Record<string | number, string | undefined>,
    // deno-lint-ignore no-explicit-any
    Record<string, any>
  >,
) => {
  const jwtFromCookie = await ctx.cookies.get("user");

  if (!jwtFromCookie) {
    ctx.response.status = 503;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Server Error.`,
      status: 503,
    };
    return;
  }

  const { user: username } = await verifyJwt(jwtFromCookie);

  const stmt = db.prepare(
    `
		SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = '${username}';
	`,
  );
  const row = stmt.get<User>();
  if (!row) {
    ctx.response.status = 503;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Server Error.`,
      status: 503,
    };
    return;
  }

  const changes = db.exec(
    `
	DELETE FROM users WHERE username = '${username}';
	`,
  );

  if (changes < 0) {
    ctx.response.status = 503;
    ctx.response.body = {
      message: `Server Error.`,
      status: 503,
    };
    return;
  }
  ctx.response.status = 200;
  ctx.response.body = {
    message: "Account deleted.",
    status: 200,
  };

  // clears up cookies
  await ctx.cookies.clear({
    httpOnly: true,
    secure: false,
    signed: false,
    sameSite: "lax",
  });

  return;
};

export default deleteAccount;
    TypeScript

    Lastly, let's create import maps for all the files located in the middleware folder.

    • middleware/auth/deleteAccount.ts
    • middleware/auth/updateAccount.ts
    • middleware/login.ts
    • middleware/register.ts

    However, creating import maps for all of these can be tedious! There is an easier way to do this.

    Head back to the root directory of your project. Head to middleware directory. Create a new file called mod.ts. Write the following code to mod.ts.

    import login from "./login.ts";
import register from "./register.ts";
import updateAccount from "./auth/updateAccount.ts";
import deleteAccount from "./auth/deleteAccount.ts";

export {
	login,
	register,
	updateAccount,
	deleteAccount
};
    TypeScript

    That should centralise all your imports in middleware!

    Open deno.json. Add the import map for ./middleware/mod.ts. Your new code should look similar to the code below.

    {
  "imports": {
    "@db/sqlite": "jsr:@db/sqlite@^0.12.0",
    "@denosaurs/argontwo": "jsr:@denosaurs/argontwo@^0.2.0",
    "@oak/oak": "jsr:@oak/oak@17.1.3",
    "@std/crypto": "jsr:@std/crypto@^1.0.3",
    "@std/dotenv": "jsr:@std/dotenv@^0.225.2",
    "@std/encoding": "jsr:@std/encoding@^1.0.5",
    "@zaubrik/djwt": "jsr:@zaubrik/djwt@^3.0.2",
    "~database": "./database/mod.ts",
    "~types/user": "./types/user.ts",
    "~types/request": "./types/request.ts",
    "~crypto/jwt": "./crypto/jwt.ts",
    "~crypto/auth": "./crypto/auth.ts",
    "~crypto/pwd": "./crypto/pwd.ts",
    "~middleware": "./middleware/mod.ts"
  }
}
    TypeScript
  • Step 7: Using the checkAuth Function

    You already have a code for checking user authentication and authorisation. You will use this for our two new routes. To do this, you will have to replace the entire code of main.ts located at the root directory of your project.

    Replace the entirety of the old code with the following code to your main.ts.

    import { Application, Router } from "@oak/oak";
import { deleteAccount, login, register, updateAccount } from "~middleware";
import checkAuth from "~crypto/auth";

const router = new Router();
const authRouter = new Router();
const app = new Application();
const controller = new AbortController();

router.get("/hello", (ctx) => {
  ctx.response.body = "Hello, World!";
});

router.get("/close", (ctx) => {
  controller.abort("User has invoked to close the connection");
  ctx.response.body = "Bye!";
});

router.post("/register", register);
router.post("/login", login);
authRouter.put("/auth/update", updateAccount);
authRouter.delete("/auth/delete", deleteAccount);

app.use(router.allowedMethods());
app.use(router.routes());
app.use(authRouter.allowedMethods());
app.use(checkAuth, authRouter.routes());

if (import.meta.main) {
  app.listen(
    {
      port: 5555,
      signal: controller.signal,
    },
  );
}
    TypeScript

    Summary

    You have learned how to write a backend server using the Oak middleware framework. Some of the key things you have learned so far are implementing basic secure routes with the cryptographic logic, doing CRUD operations with register, updateAccount and deleteAccount using sqlite module, and lastly, writing import maps that make imports easier to write.

    Before you head over to the final step, install the VSCode plugin, SQLite Viewer. You can use this SQLite Viewer plugin to observe the changes in the database while you follow the instructions below.

    #1 Generate a new TOKEN.

    Run the following command.

    deno run generateToken.ts

    Paste the token to the .env file by replacing the old one. For example, if your new token is "FOO", and your old token is "YOUR_NEW_TOKEN", you must replace it with your "YOUR_NEW_TOKEN" with "FOO".

    #2 Restart the backend server

    Close the previous one and run the following command.

    deno run -A main.ts

    #3 Open a new terminal. Register a user with your StackUp username using curl command. Replace "StackUpUsername" with your StackUp username before running the command below.

    curl -i -XPOST -d '{"username": "StackUpUsername", "password": "123"}' --url http://127.0.0.1:5555/register

    #4 Login the new user that has your StackUp Username

    curl -i -XPOST -d '{"username": "StackUpUsername", "password": "123"}' --url http://127.0.0.1:5555/login --cookie-jar cookie.cookie

    There will be a file created called cookie.cookie. Open the file. Copy the JWT signature from the cookie. See screenshot below for what it looks like. You must copy the WHOLE string.

    #5 Update the user's username by appending "-Ready-For-Submission" e.g. "StackUpUsername-Ready-For-Submission". Replace "yourJWTString" with your JWT signature you copied previously before running the command below.

    curl -i -XPUT -d '{"username": "StackUpUsername-Ready-For-Submission", "password": "123"}' --url http://127.0.0.1:5555/auth/update --cookie cookie.cookie -H "Authorization: Bearer yourJWTString"

    You have to relogin after this with the new username. Replace "StackUpUsername" with your StackUp username before running the command below.

    curl -i -XPOST -d '{"username": "StackUpUsername-Ready-For-Submission", "password": "123"}' --url http://127.0.0.1:5555/login --cookie-jar cookie.cookie

    Copy the new JWT signature in cookie.cookie.

    #6 Delete the user by calling the appropriate route path. Replace "yourJWTString" with your JWT signature you copied previously before running the command below.

    curl -i -XDELETE --url "http://127.0.0.1:5555/auth/delete" --cookie cookie.cookie -H "Authorization: Bearer yourJWTString"

    Check the following video demo below if you have followed the instructions correctly. Ensure you have the -i flag for your curl command which may not be evident in the video demonstration.
